1 science, technology, engineering and mathematics curriculum and
2 vocational training to create a career path in horticulture;
3 (2) Development and implementation of science, technology,
4 engineering, arts and mathematics curricula that incorporate the use
5 of a school garden;
6 (3) Development and implementation of training that may be
7 provided to a group or individually to teachers in how to establish
8 and maintain school gardens to increase the time teachers allocate to
9 teaching science, technology, engineering and mathematics; and
10 (4) Development and implementation of a food safety plan
11 designed to ensure that food grown in a school garden is properly
12 handled and safe to sell and consume;
13 (b) Pay for any travel expenses associated with the attendance of
14 a teacher at any training or conference relating to school gardens;
15 and
16 (c) Pay for the costs of a conference regarding school gardens
17 held in this State.
18 5. As used in this section:
19 (a) “Public school” has the meaning ascribed to it in
20 NRS 385.007.
21 (b) “School garden” includes, without limitation, a hydroponic
22 garden.
